<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/4752216-joshua-d"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1589054404i/4752216._UY100_CR38,0,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/4752216-joshua-d">Joshua D</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">Nope. Not any more than you&apos;d need to be familiar with Norse mythology enjoy Thor comics. At most, someone familiar with the myths might get a kick ou<a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">…more</a></span><span class="fullContent">Nope. Not any more than you'd need to be familiar with Norse mythology enjoy Thor comics. At most, someone familiar with the myths might get a kick out of seeing familiar names and concepts, but that's about it. I disagree with the other commentators that knowing much about the subject will harm the book. The book isn't meant to be a retelling of the myths.<a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
